  "doc_id": "28342",
  "text": "Previous lesion and inactivation studies have shown involvement of the DMS in response selection [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] and response inhibition [CITATION_3] . Thus, animals lacking a functional DMS display various forms of disinhibited behavior. Of particular interest are the findings that a DMS lesion impairs [CITATION_4] , whereas treatment with methylphenidate improve stop signal reaction time task performance [CITATION_5] . These findings echo the effects of methylphenidate , which reduces social play, and intra-DMS DNQX, which enhances it (present study). We do not think that DMS inactivation causes an overall disinhibition of behavior. In the present study, the effects of intra-DMS DNQX on social play were behaviorally specific, as no changes were observed in social exploration and locomotor activity. Moreover, animals with DMS lesions show no change in responding for food under a progressive ratio schedule of reinforcement [CITATION_6] , and operant responding remains sensitive to presentation of reward-associated stimuli after DMS inactivation (although the specificity of responding is impaired; [CITATION_7] . Together, these data suggest that DMS mechanisms exert inhibitory control over vigorous forms of behavior, such as social play, but that inactivation or lesion of the DMS leaves the structure of behavior and its appropriateness to the situation intact [CITATION_8] .",
